},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111239"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever, malaise and severe pain on swallowing. She reports difficulty opening her mouth and limited oral intake. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 94/min, blood pressure 110/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. She is drooling and has a muffled voice. There is trismus with limited jaw opening. Examination of the oropharynx reveals unilateral soft palate swelling with deviation of the uvula to the contralateral side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supportive treatment with regular analgesia and intravenous fluids","Discharge with oral analgesia and review in 48 hours","Immediate airway assessment and intubation","Dexamethasone and antibiotics with urgent ENT consultation","Oral antibiotics with ENT outpatient review"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of peritonsillar abscess (quinsy), characterised by trismus, drooling, and a muffled \u0027hot potato\u0027 voice. The unilateral soft palate swelling with uvular deviation is pathognomonic - soft palate swelling due to a blocked and infected Weber\u0027s gland pushes the tonsils inferiorly and makes them difficult to examine. While this condition typically develops as a complication of acute tonsillitis, it represents a more serious infection requiring prompt intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone and antibiotics with urgent ENT consultation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. A single dose of corticosteroid reduces inflammation and trismus, facilitating subsequent examination and drainage. Empiric antibiotics are essential to treat the underlying infection. ENT consultation is required as most cases will need incision and drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive treatment with regular analgesia and intravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate and risks progression of the infection to deep neck spaces. While supportive care is important, specific intervention is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge with oral analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous as these patients require close monitoring and specific treatment to prevent complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate airway assessment and intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is overly aggressive for most cases of quinsy. While airway compromise can occur, it is rare and usually develops gradually with warning signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics with ENT outpatient review\u003C/strong\u003E provides insufficient treatment intensity for this condition. The presence of an abscess requires consideration of drainage, and outpatient management risks clinical deterioration. Furthermore, patients with quinsy require a single corticosteroid dose alongside their antibiotic treatment. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peritonsillar abscess (quinsy) is characterized by trismus, drooling, and muffled \u0027hot potato\u0027 voice.","Initial management of quinsy includes both corticosteroids and antibiotics to reduce inflammation and treat infection.","Urgent ENT consultation is required for consideration of incision and drainage in patients with quinsy."],"references":["Akhavan, M., 2021. Ear, Nose, Throat. Emergency Medicine Clinics of North America, 39, pp.661-675.","Powell, J. and Wilson, J., 2012. An evidence-based review of peritonsillar abscess. Clinical Otolaryngology, 37(2), pp.136-145. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22321140/","Wald E., 2022. Peritonsillar cellulitis and abscess. UptoDate. Viewed at January 2023. Available via: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/peritonsillar-cellulitis-and-abscess?search=quinsy\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~54\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93371"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11908"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93371"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-11T19:26:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-11T19:31:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4504"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111239"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40